Why does the first implementation not work? The second line could construct the `const char*` into a `std::string`, then into a `A`, and finally `B`.

Note 1: The values of the types that are implicitly castable are the same values, the type only represents that the value has passed a pre-condition, holds it&#39;s condition through operations, and propogates that condition through operations on similar types. The implicit casting is allowed for types to other types with weaker pre-conditions.

