You can use [`explode()`][1] on your indexes and create a new array, then you can achieve your desired output.

**Example:**

    &lt;?
    //your array
    $array[&#39;remove_0&#39;] = &#39;on&#39;;
    $array[&#39;token_0&#39;] = &#39;123&#39;;
    $array[&#39;reason_0&#39;] = &#39;Expired&#39;;
    $array[&#39;remove_1&#39;] = &#39;on&#39;;
    $array[&#39;token_1&#39;] = &#39;456&#39;;
    $array[&#39;reason_1&#39;] = &#39;Removed&#39;;
    
    $newArray = array();
    foreach ($array as $key =&gt; $value) {
      $groupExplode = explode(&quot;_&quot;,$key); // explode with &quot;_&quot;
      $newArray[$groupExplode[1]][] = $value; // save data in a new array
    }
    
    foreach ($newArray as $key =&gt; $value) {
      echo $value[1].&quot; | &quot;.$value[2]. &quot;&lt;br/&gt;&quot;;
    }
    ?&gt;

**Result:**

    123 | Expired
    456 | Removed

**Side note:** but its better to optimize your `$_POST` values.


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.explode.php

